PestDescription: Ants that build nests in trees and wooden structues by chewing tunnels through them.
Species of stinging ants whose venom may cause anaphylactic shock in those allergic to it.
Species of ants that are often found indoors scavenging for food.
Species of solitary wasps native to the eastern Untied States that parasitize beneficial wasps and bees. Female velet ants have no wings and can inflict multiple extremely painful stings.
A species of eusocial wasps native to North America that prey on caterpillars and other insects. Can be found under structures building either cone or umbrella shaped nests out of paper.
Eusocial wasps that build nests out of paper. Typically, they are more docile than yellowjackets but will respond agressively if their nest is threatened.
A species of solitary mud dauber wasps that prey on spiders. Often found building organ pipe shaped nests out of mud on trees or structures.

Species of solitary mud dauber wasps that can be found building cylindrical nests out of mud. They are docile unless threatened. Mud daubers can typically be differentiated from other wasps by their long and narrow waist.
Species of bright yellow and black (or black and white) social wasps that predate on pest insects. They are highly agressive and often build their nests underground.
A species of domesticated social bees that produce honey and are invasive in the United States. Generally docile but their stings may cause anaphylactic shock in those allergic to it.
A species of social or solitary bees that build their nest in wood and often cause structure damage.
A hybrid derived from the European honey bee (Apis mellifera) that can be found in the southern United States. These bees are highly aggresive and getting stung too many times can be fatal.
Species of solitary bees that build their nests out of leaf cuttings. Their nest building can damage garden plants and crops.
A large species of cat that can be found in the western United States and parts of Florida. Often avoids people, but fatal attacks have occured.
A medium-sized species of cat native to North America. Bobcats tend to fear people and attacks are rarely fatal, but they may pose a risk to children and pets.
A species of wild pigs often found in the southwest United States. Whether alone or in packs, they can be a nuisance in the garden or fatally atack people and pets.
A species of wild pigs that can be found in the west and southeast of the United States. Attacks on humans are rare but can be fatal due to their tusks and their agression.
A nocturnal mammal found throughout North America and often in places where people inhabit. They are prone to rabies, pose a risk to pets, and tend to cause structural damage when they nest in homes.
A species of small canine found throughout North America. Attacks on humans are rare and generally minor; however, coyotes pose a serious risk to livestock and pets.
A species of small canine native to North America. Foxes are prone to rabies may attack livestock and pets.
A flowering plant native to North America. Leaves of poison ivy contain a sap that causes skin irritation and rashes; as such, they should be avoided.

The American black bear is the smallest bear in North America and typically live in largely forested areas. Though they are generally docile, attacks on people are possible but they rarely lead to serious injury.

A species of pit viper native to the southeastern United Stated. They are typically found in moist areas near water, such as swamps and lakes. Bites from the cottonmouth can potentially be fatal and require emergency care.
A species of hawk moth found throughout North America. The caterpillars of this moth can often be found on tobacco and tomato plants which they eat.
